description: {"blocks":[{"key":"eju75","text":"Insilico drug design has been a catalyst in developing novel chemicals, Phyto-actives, nanoparticles, and anti-sense oligonucleotides. A robust screening setup increases the chances of success of every project. In recent years, anti-sense oligonucleotides (ASO) have provided a major breakthrough in developing 10 ASO drugs that are FDA-approved. This prompts us to develop a protocol for ASO design, docking, and MD simulation studies. The protocol has been divided into 6 sub-sections inclusive of 30 steps. The tools used in the protocol are either open-source or academic free version. The protocol is developed and validated on GPU workstation using NVIDIA A100","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"4st8r","text":" Identification of preferable mRNA local secondary structures for ASO binding.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":1,"length":77}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"c9u9f","text":"      ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7pgj0","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3s1ud","text":"       a.An effective ASO should be designed at the regions where mRNA is accessible for hybridization.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2ho2b","text":"        b.The accessible sites are identified using the secondary structure of the RNA. Local structures accessible to ASOs are those usually located at the terminal end, internal loops, joint sequences, hairpins and bulges of 10 or more consecutive nucleotides.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"akfhs","text":"        c.After confirmation of the accessible conserved local secondary structures and the corresponding sequences of ASOs (approximately 20 bp), one can settle on some well-defined activity enhancing motifs and discard those activity decreasing motifs in the ASOs. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"93p3a","text":"        d.Studies have found a positive correlation between ASO-mediated mRNA knockdown and the presence of CCAC, TCCC, ACTC, GCCA and CTCT motifs in the ASOs. Conversely, the presence of GGGG (G-quartets formation), ACTG, AAA and TAA motifs in ASOs weakened ASO activity. Studies also showed strong ASO effects with a minimum of 11 G or C residues in 20 bp ASOs, whereas poor inhibition was observed by ASOs having nine or fewer G or C residues.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6p3pc","text":"        e.The tool Soligopresent in the server, Sfold predicts accessible sites on the target RNA for ASO binding. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":19,"length":6},{"style":"italic","offset":48,"length":5}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5uj7f","text":"                  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f6mt2","text":"                    i.The user can directly enter the target mRNA sequence in the server or upload a file containing the sequence in FASTA format.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"asbg","text":"                    ii.The batch mode allows the entry of up to 10,000 bases.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1n0tc","text":"                    iii.The user can specify the desired length of the antisense oligonuceotides ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"65imt","text":"  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"9lu6h","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4sclm","text":"                    iv.An accessible site can be targeted by a number of antisense oligonucleotides, selection of the \"optimal\" one can be based on binding energy, together with other empirical rules such as GC content, avoidance of GGGG (or more stringent GGG) motifs, etc.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"b9eb7","text":"                    v.Stronger binding is indicated by smaller binding energy (stacking energies are negatively valued). To design a potent ASO, the binding energy between the ASO and mRNA should be -8 kcal/mol.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":101,"length":17}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"e7rdg","text":"                    vi.The antisense oligo binding energy is a weighted sum of the DNA/RNA stacking energies for the hybrid formed by the antisense oligo and the targeted sequence. For a base-pair stack, the weight for the sum is calculated by the probability of the unpaired dinucleotide in the target sequence that is involved in the stack. This weighting scheme accounts for the structural variation at the target site among the structures in the sample.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"aegup","text":"                    vii.The output has the following filter criteria:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9h6av","text":"                            o   40% ≤ GC % ≤ 60%;","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"e3f1f","text":"                            o   Antisense oligo binding energy ≤  -8 kcal/mol.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6h1i9","text":"                            o   No GGGG in the target sequence.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cq5uh","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6m0m8","text":"  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":1,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"2hbql","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cr165","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4ohd5","text":"         f.The software OligoWalk can be used to calculate the thermodynamic properties between ASO and target mRNA sequence. {"blocks":[{"key":"1pmou","text":"Docking of target mRNA and ASO.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":31}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1gi79","text":"       ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"e75bq","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7h6h2","text":"        a.Select the best predicted ASOs based on the steps above for further docking and simulation.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1kie3","text":"         b.Nucleic acid-Nucleic acid docking can be done using the HNADOCK Server web interface. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5b945","text":"               ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"c894m","text":"                 i.Secondary Structure Prediction: By default, the server uses the \"RNAfold\" to predict the secondary structure of an RNA sequence for ab-initio three-dimensional structural modeling if no template is found for the sequence. Users may also choose other secondary structure prediction method like Fold, MaxExpect, ProbKnot, and IPKnot, where Fold, MaxExpect, and ProbKnot are taken from the RNAstructure package.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":19,"length":31}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2r9q1","text":"                ii.RNA-ASO Interaction Prediction: By default, HNADOCK server builds the complex structures between two RNAs without prior binding information through ab initio docking. However, the server also offers users an option to choose a method (RNAup or RactIP) for RNA-RNA interaction predictions. The predicted interaction information will be then used as inter-RNA distance constrains during docking.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":19,"length":31}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"685op","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1v46b","text":"Note: A) RNAup calculates the thermodynamics of RNA−ASO interactions, by decomposing the binding into two stages. (1) First the probability that a potential binding sites remains unpaired (equivalent to the free energy needed to open the site) is computed. (2) Then this accessibility is combined with the interaction energy to obtain the total binding energy. All calculations are done by computing partition functions over all possible conformations.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":6}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9qqt1","text":"B) RactIP is a prediction method for RNA-ASO interaction of general type using integer programming. RactIP can integrate approximate information on an ensemble of equilibrium joint structures into the objective function of integer programming using posterior internal and external base-paring probabilities.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3aoba","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"f3a2e","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8u1ba","text":"HNADOCK Reference : He J, Wang J, Tao H, Xiao Y, Huang SY.
